		{"id":"fc3c9eda237fc887","type":"text","text":"#### Host-only Network adapter\nThe VM will be assigned one IP, but it's only accessible by the box VM is running on. No other computers can access it.\n\n#### Bridge only Network adapter\nYour VM will be in the same network as your host, if your host IP is 172.16.120.45 then your VM will be like 172.16.120.50 It can be accessed by all computers in your host network.\n\n#### NAT\nJust like your home network with a wireless router, the VM will be assigned in separate subnet, like 192.168.6.1 is your host computer, and VM is 192.168.6.3, then your VM can access outside network like your host, but no outside access to your VM directly, it's protected\n\n\n![[Pasted image 20250125163557.png]]\n\n#### DHCP is used to assign the IP addresses automatically","x":-710,"y":-1160,"width":770,"height":760},
		{"id":"b3f3b7f43fbf6cb9","type":"text","text":"```\n1. nmcli dev status\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This command shows you all the connected network devices to machine\n```\n\n![[Pasted image 20250125164901.png]]\n\n```\n2. cd /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This command shows you network device that are connected. If we add new network device then to use it in machine we need to configure deviced connection in this file \n```\n\n![[Pasted image 20250125223314.png]]\n\n```\n3. cat ifcfg-ens160\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ You will see so many configuration related to ifcfg-ens160 \n```\n\n\n## Method we have to assigning the IP addresses\n1. `GUI` --> can assign IP addresses and also can manage the network connection\n2. `nmtui` --> can only manage the connection not the devices\n3. `nmcli` \n4. `vieditor` using vi-editor we can configure manually\n \n","x":-710,"y":-280,"width":770,"height":800},
		{"id":"43590537d5b62d1b","type":"text","text":"# How to add new network adapter (Network device)\n\n![[Pasted image 20250125225324.png]]\n\n```\n1. click on add \nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ see the mouse cursor on image\n```\n\n![[Pasted image 20250125225417.png]]\n\n```\n2. choose network adapter option and then click on finish button and you will see\n```\n\n![[Pasted image 20250125225551.png]]\n\n```\n3. choose any option NAT, Host-only, Custom\n```\n\n```\n4. login to device and run \n   ls\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ It won't work because we need to convert new network adapter into connection\n```\n\n```\n5. nmcli dev status\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ You will see ðŸ‘‡ðŸ‘‡ see the newly connected network adaptor status is isconnected we need to connect it\n```\n\n![[Pasted image 20250125230106.png]]\n\n```\n6. nmcli device show\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ Shows you full device details\ndevice --> device is something that is attached to system like NIC card\n```\n\n```\n7. nmcli connection show\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ Shows you connection details\nconnection --> connection is something that we made to access the devices\n```\n\n","x":80,"y":-280,"width":770,"height":2280},
		{"id":"8f91e1e1e115b7ce","type":"text","text":"```\n1. ifconfig\n2. ip a\n3. ip addr\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ Used to check the details of IP-address of device\n```\n\n```\n1. nmcli con show\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This command shows you the connection details\n\n2. nmcli con show -a\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This command shows you the details of active connection \n\n3. nmcli c s\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This command shows you the details of active connection\nc --> connection\ns --> show\n\n4. nmcli connection up <connection-name>\n   nmcli connection up ens160\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This command up meaning activate the connection\n\n```\n\n# Making new connection\n\n```\n1. nmcli device status\n```\n\n![[Pasted image 20250126020932.png]]\n\n```\n2. nmcli con add type ethernet con-name ens224 ifname ens224\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ Making connection of device ens224 \ntype erthernet is the type of connection\ncon-name is the name of connection\nifname ens224 is the interface meaning device name. Meaning for which interface i want to make the connection\n\n3. nmcli connection show\n```\n\n![[Pasted image 20250126021554.png]]\n\n```\n4. ip a\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ To check whether IP is allocated or not \n```\n\n![[Pasted image 20250126021737.png]]\n\n```\n5. ping 192.168.58.133\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ Checking whether allocated IP is working fine or not\n```\n\n```\n6. Very important point ---> The IP that is assigned to connection is assign by VM-ware DHCP server not by router.\nIn case of NAT and Host-only VM-ware assign the IP address and In case of Bridge, router DHCP assign the IP \n```\n\n```\n7. ifdown <connection-name>\n   ifdown ens224\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This command down meaning deactivate connection\n\n8. ifup <connection-name>\n   ifup ens224\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This command up meaning activate the connection\n```","x":863,"y":-274,"width":857,"height":2054},
		{"id":"913b3a220fc9f5a7","type":"text","text":"# Making connection using Static IP \nIn earlier example DHCP assigned the IP. This time we assign the IP manually\n\n```\n1. nmcli con add type ethernet con-name static2 ifname ens224 ip4 192.168.0.50/24 gw4 192.168.0.1\n\n* type ethernet --> type is ethernet\n* con-name --> static2\n* interface name --> ens224\n* ip4 192.168.0.50/24 --> assigning IP 4 with subnet mask\n* gw4 192.168.0.1 --> internet gateway 4   \n\n2. nmcli con mod static2 ipv4.dns \"8.8.8.8.8.8.4.4\"\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ Assigning DNS \n\n3. nmcli con down static2\n4. nmcli con up static2\n   \n5. nmcli connection show\n```\n\n![[Pasted image 20250126024224.png]]\n\n```\n1. cat ifcfg-static2\n```\n\n![[Pasted image 20250126034546.png]]\n\n```\nTo change the ONBOOT option we can run\n\n1. nmcli con mod static2 connection.autoconnect no\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This will change the ONBOOT=yes to ONBOOT=no\n```\n\n# How to give permission to user over network connection\n\n```\n1. nmcli con mod static2 connection.permissions <user-name>\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This will give the permission to single user\n\n2. nmcli con mod static2 connection.permissions user:<user-name-1>, <user-name-2>\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This will give the permission to multiple user and keep in mind in connection.permissions user:<user-name-1> there is no-space in between connection.permissions user:<user-name-1>\n\n3. nmcli con reload\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This will reload all the connections\n\n4. nmcli con edit static2\nðŸ‘‰ðŸ‘‰ This will allow you to modify the connection interactively\n```\n\n# If i want to remove the DNS of connection\n\n```\n1. nmcli con mod static2 -ipv4.dns 8.8.8.8.8.8.4.4\n```\n\n# Deleting connection \n\n```\n1. nmcli con del static2\n```","x":1760,"y":-274,"width":1060,"height":2174},
